  <content>
    <title>Business Process Analysis - Enterprise Scale and Governance</title>

    <summary>A five-stage methodology for documenting how work actually flows through an organization (current state), classifying each step as value-adding, business-necessary, or non-value-adding, and designing a measurable future state. At enterprise scale (M&amp;A, ERP rollout, digital transformation), a portfolio agent maintains the process inventory while per-process agents apply the 5-stage loop against APQC PCF or SCOR reference frameworks.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Processes trapped in tribal knowledge produce inconsistent execution and hide inefficiencies. Quantifying NVA percentage before redesigning separates evidence-based improvement from gut-feel reorganizations. The nva_minutes_per_year *feasibility composite score prioritizes which processes to deep-model versus document narratively only, preventing portfolio bloat.</p>
      <p>Processes without documented current state become post-implementation arguments about what changed; without baseline metrics the business case for improvement is undefendable; without a design gate stage 5 (validation) implementations chase incorrect process models.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>M&amp;A integration requiring a Day-1/Day-100/target-state process comparison across two organizations' inventories.</item>
        <item>ERP/CRM/HCM rollout (SAP S/4HANA, Oracle Fusion, Workday) - gap-fit analysis against vendor reference processes.</item>
        <item>Digital transformation programme: 100-500 processes scored on maturity, automation readiness, and customer impact.</item>
        <item>Pre-IPO/pre-acquisition due diligence (SOX 404, ISO 9001) requiring auditor-grade process narratives with control points.</item>
        <item>Shared-services/GBS design consolidating multiple business units into one process model.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-team local workflow - use the ba-modeling/business-process-analysis variant; enterprise governance overhead is unjustified.</item>
        <item>Greenfield startup with no installed process estate - jump to use-case-modeling or user-story-mapping.</item>
        <item>Pure customer-experience redesign - use customer-journey-mapping; BPA is a downstream consequence.</item>
        <item>Single broken process instance requiring root-cause analysis - use 5-whys/fishbone instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="five-stage-loop">
      <p>Business Process Analysis follows a repeatable five-stage loop, applied per-process within a portfolio-agent orchestration framework.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before modeling any individual process, build a scoped inventory table with columns: process name, owner, priority, in-scope flag. Prioritize by nva_minutes_per_year and strategic fit; deep-model only the top decile.</statement>
        <rationale>Enterprise programs routinely discover 800+ processes; without a Pareto cut, documentation effort consumes more resources than the improvements deliver. The scorecard prevents portfolio bloat.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Stage 1: Identify Processes</p>
      <list>
        <item>Build the process inventory by interviewing business unit heads, reviewing org charts, and mining existing SOP repositories.</item>
        <item>Score each process by nva_minutes_per_year (volume *cycle_time *nva_pct) and strategic fit to the transformation goal.</item>
        <item>Deep-model only the top decile; document the rest at narrative depth (one paragraph each) to prevent portfolio bloat.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Stage 2: Document Current State</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Capture every workaround and exception, not just the official flow; record verbatim quotes from process participants for any anomaly in evidence/anomalies.md.</statement>
        <rationale>Shadow steps and workarounds are the actual process; documenting only the intended flow produces a diagram nobody recognizes and analysis based on fiction. Verbatim quotes prevent agent rewrites that erase institutional knowledge.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Activities - what is done.</item>
        <item>Actors - who does it (person, role, or system).</item>
        <item>Inputs and outputs - data entering and leaving each step.</item>
        <item>Decisions and business rules - gateway logic with conditions.</item>
        <item>Systems used - applications touched at each step.</item>
        <item>Exceptions and workarounds - deviations from the official flow.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Stage 3: Analyze the Process</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Classify every step as Value-Adding (VA), Business-Necessary (BN), or Non-Value-Adding (NVA); compute NVA percentage before proposing any improvement.</statement>
        <rationale>Redesigning before quantifying NVA produces a wish list, not a business case. The NVA percentage anchors the expected-benefit calculation in Stage 4.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Value analysis - which steps add direct customer or business value (VA), which are required but not directly valuable (BN, e.g., compliance), which are waste (NVA).</item>
        <item>Time analysis - where are delays; compute cycle time vs. touch time ratio.</item>
        <item>Cost analysis - cost per transaction at each step.</item>
        <item>Quality analysis - where errors occur and their rework cost.</item>
        <item>Pain point analysis - participant frustrations (captured from elicitation, not inferred).</item>
      </list>

      <p>Stage 4: Design Future State</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Produce a structured diff table (step | current actor | future actor | current system | future system | change type | risk | dependency) instead of a narrative description.</statement>
        <rationale>A narrative future state hides integration prerequisites; the diff table forces specificity and makes dependencies visible before implementation starts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Eliminate - remove NVA steps (e.g., redundant approvals, double-entry).</item>
        <item>Automate - replace manual steps with technology where ROI is positive.</item>
        <item>Parallelize - run sequential steps concurrently where data dependencies allow.</item>
        <item>Simplify - reduce decision complexity by raising thresholds or merging branches.</item>
        <item>Integrate - connect systems to eliminate manual handoffs.</item>
        <item>Standardize - enforce one consistent execution path to eliminate variation-driven rework.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Stage 5: Validate and Plan</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Do not advance to Stage 5 without Stage 4 review by the portfolio agent (enterprise context) or process owner (project context); validation is a decision gate, not a formality.</statement>
        <rationale>Future-state designs based on incorrect process models or unverified business rules generate implementation work in the wrong direction; the stage gate catches these before any code is written.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Review future state with process owners and affected stakeholders.</item>
        <item>Identify system requirements generated by the redesign.</item>
        <item>Define transition plan: how the organization moves from current to future state.</item>
        <item>Define success metrics: quantitative targets against current baseline.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="portfolio-agent-orchestration">
      <p>Enterprise BPA uses a two-tier orchestration pattern to prevent portfolio bloat and ensure consistency across dozens or hundreds of processes.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run enterprise BPA as two-tier orchestration: a portfolio agent that maintains the inventory and governance artifacts, plus per-process agents (one invocation per in-scope process) applying the 5-stage loop.</statement>
        <rationale>A single agent attempting to model 100+ processes in one context produces shallow, hallucinated artifacts. The portfolio agent acts as coordinator - it assigns scope, enforces the BPMN standard, and rolls up metrics; per-process agents produce the deliverables.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Limit deep-modeling to the top decile by nva_minutes_per_year *strategic_fit; document all other processes at narrative depth (one paragraph each).</statement>
        <rationale>Full documentation of a 500-process landscape is unmaintainable; the Pareto principle applied to NVA impact identifies the 10% of processes delivering 80% of improvement value.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Portfolio scorecard">
        <code lang="csv">pcf_l2_code,pcf_l2_name,owner,maturity_pemm,volume_per_year,cycle_time_min,nva_pct,automation_candidate_score,risk_score,decision
1.1.1,Define the business concept,VP Strategy,P-2,4,2880,55,2,4,review
1.3.5,Manage customer master data,Data Office,P-3,12000,18,40,5,3,redesign
2.4.2,Process accounts payable,Finance Ops,P-2,180000,9,62,5,2,automate</code>
        <note>Prioritize by nva_minutes_per_year (volume *cycle_time *nva_pct) and automation score; reserve deep-modeling capacity for the top processes only.</note>
      </example>

      <p>The portfolio agent role:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Maintains the process inventory and scorecard.</item>
        <item>Enforces BPMN standards and naming conventions across all per-process agents.</item>
        <item>Assigns stage-gate approvals - no process advances from stage 4 to 5 without portfolio agent review.</item>
        <item>Rolls up process metrics into heat maps, maturity matrices, and automation-candidate rankings.</item>
        <item>For M&amp;A: maintains a per-L2 ownership decision log (acquirer | target | hybrid | new) with deal-thesis citations.</item>
        <item>For ERP: maintains gap-fit analysis comparing as-is processes to vendor reference processes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="bpmn-governance">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Decide level-of-detail (L1/L2/L3/L4), naming convention (verb-noun), pool/lane discipline, and message-flow rules before any modelling starts; put the rules in standards/bpmn-conventions.md and have every agent read them.</statement>
        <rationale>BPMN files produced without a shared dialect are incompatible at the portfolio level; a governance board that approves diagrams with inconsistent conventions creates technical debt in the model repository.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat BPMN as code: source-control XML, run bpmnlint in CI, code-review changes, tag releases per programme milestone.</statement>
        <rationale>BPMN files without version history cannot answer "what changed and why?" - the audit trail required by ISO 9001 and SOX 404 auditors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="reference-framework-alignment">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Anchor to APQC PCF, SCOR, or eTOM as scaffolding, not law; for every deviation from the reference, capture rationale and competitive-differentiation hypothesis.</statement>
        <rationale>Reference-model fundamentalism forces genuine differentiators into generic boxes, destroying competitive advantage documentation. The deviation log is the intellectual property of the BPA exercise.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Lifting APQC PCF text verbatim as if it describes the actual company processes.</description>
        <reason>Reference processes are industry averages; the company's reality may differ significantly. Every reference-derived sentence must be tagged [reference] and reviewed by a human before publication.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="m-a-specialization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Maintain a per-L2-process ownership decision log with entries: acquirer | target | hybrid | new, each citing a deal-thesis line; un-cited decisions are blocked.</statement>
        <rationale>M&amp;A process decisions made without deal-thesis grounding reflect political convenience rather than value creation; the citation requirement enforces discipline and provides audit evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>M&amp;A process comparison workflow:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Map both inventories to APQC PCF Level 2.</item>
        <item>For every PCF L2 row, fill: acquirer_owner, target_owner, decision (adopt-acquirer | adopt-target | hybrid | new), rationale (cite deal-thesis line).</item>
        <item>Flag any L2 with no owner on either side as "GAP - requires design".</item>
        <item>Output: portfolio.csv + decisions-log.md.</item>
        <item>Do NOT model individual processes until the portfolio agent approves the ownership decisions.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="erp-rollout-specialization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For ERP gap-fit analysis, follow: adopt-standard → configure → extend → build-custom → drop; document each gap with explicit decision type. Agents bias toward "build" - counter with explicit configure-first prompts.</statement>
        <rationale>Every customization multiplies upgrade cost; the adopt/configure priority order ensures the lowest-cost option is evaluated before custom development is authorized.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-and-limits">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Documenting the ideal process instead of the actual process.</description>
        <reason>Analysis of an ideal state produces improvements to a process nobody runs; the current-state documentation must reflect observed reality, not policy intent.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping baseline metrics before redesigning.</description>
        <reason>Future-state benefits have no evidence anchor without volume, cycle time, and cost baselines; the business case is undefendable.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Cross-country process smoothing: treating a multi-jurisdiction process as one global flow.</description>
        <reason>Tax, payroll, and labor law vary significantly by country; a global process diagram that hides legal variants creates compliance risk and failed implementations.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Portfolio inflation without Pareto cut.</description>
        <reason>Enterprise programmes routinely "discover" 800+ processes; LLMs eagerly produce documentation for all of them. Without a Pareto cut, the artefact set is unmaintainable.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Reference-model fundamentalism.</description>
        <reason>Forcing every business onto APQC PCF or SCOR distorts genuine differentiators. Reference frameworks are scaffolding, not law.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Governance theatre without instrumentation.</description>
        <reason>A BPMN governance board produces standards nobody uses. The methodology cannot, by itself, prove adoption - instrumentation (audit trails, conformance checks) is required.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Politics-shaped diagrams in M&amp;A.</description>
        <reason>In M&amp;A, the surviving entity's process is documented as canonical even when the acquired entity's is better. The methodology has no political guard-rails.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Static snapshot without maintenance cycle.</description>
        <reason>Enterprise process landscapes drift quarterly (re-orgs, system changes, regulation). A 6-month-old BPA is already stale unless actively maintained.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <p>Recommended tooling for enterprise BPA:</p>
      <list>
        <item>pm4py - Process mining, conformance, BPMN 2.0 XML generation.</item>
        <item>bpmn-to-image - Render BPMN XML → SVG/PNG for stakeholder review packets.</item>
        <item>bpmnlint - Validate BPMN files against governance rules.</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli (mmdc) - Quick L1/L2 portfolio overviews.</item>
        <item>pandas + pyjanitor - Portfolio scoring tables, maturity heat maps.</item>
        <item>openpyxl - Read vendor accelerator workbooks (SAP Signavio, Oracle MBP).</item>
        <item>pdfplumber / python-docx - Extract process steps from existing SOP / due-diligence packs.</item>
        <item>whisper.cpp - Transcribe stakeholder interviews and steering-committee recordings.</item>
        <item>jq + csvkit - Slice ERP / CRM event-log exports.</item>
        <item>git + dvc - Version BPMN, evidence, and analysis artefacts.</item>
      </list>

      <p>SaaS platforms supporting BPA at scale:</p>
      <list>
        <item>SAP Signavio (Process Manager + Insights + Journey Modeler) - De-facto enterprise standard; deep value-stream + variant analytics.</item>
        <item>Celonis EMS - Industry leader for log-based discovery and conformance.</item>
        <item>Software AG ARIS - Long-standing enterprise BPM; strong governance metadata.</item>
        <item>iGrafx - Mid-market enterprise BPM with simulation.</item>
        <item>Camunda 8 (SaaS / self-host) - Open BPMN 2.0; pairs well with implementation phase.</item>
        <item>Apromore - Open-source process mining; pairs with pm4py.</item>
        <item>UiPath Process Mining - Strongest tie-in if RPA is part of the future state.</item>
        <item>Microsoft Process Insights / Power Automate Process Mining - Default if shop is Microsoft 365-centric.</item>
        <item>LeanIX / Ardoq - EA tools; pair process portfolio with application portfolio (TIME assessment).</item>
        <item>ServiceNow APM + Process Mining - If ServiceNow is the system of record for IT/HR.</item>
        <item>Mega HOPEX - Heavy GRC + risk integration; audit-grade but bureaucratic.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Pareto the inventory first. Score every L2 process; deep-model only the top decile by nva_minutes_per_year *strategic_fit. Document the rest at narrative depth only (one paragraph each).</item>
        <item>Pin the BPMN dialect early. Decide level-of-detail (L1 / L2 / L3 / L4), naming convention (verb-noun), pool/lane discipline, and message-flow rules before any modelling starts. Put the rules in standards/bpmn-conventions.md and have every agent read them.</item>
        <item>Anchor to a reference framework, but score the deviation. APQC PCF / SCOR / eTOM are anchors, not laws. For every deviation from the reference, capture rationale + competitive-differentiation hypothesis.</item>
        <item>Couple process to application portfolio. A process that runs on 5 redundant systems is the application-rationalisation case, not just a process case. Cross-link to LeanIX / Ardoq / your CMDB.</item>
        <item>Make conformance the default validator. Once an event log exists, run pm4py / Celonis monthly against the modelled BPMN. Conformance &lt; 80% → re-document, don't argue.</item>
        <item>Quantify before redesigning. Future-state without baseline metrics is a wish list. Demand volume + cycle + cost; if data is missing, run a sampling pilot.</item>
        <item>Diff future-vs-current as a structured table. Columns: step | current actor | future actor | current system | future system | change type | risk | dependency. Forces specificity and reveals integration prerequisites.</item>
        <item>For ERP rollouts: gap-fit, then config-fit, then customise-only-as-last-resort. Document each gap as adopt-standard / configure / extend / build / drop. Agents bias toward "build" - counter with explicit configure-first prompts.</item>
        <item>For M&amp;A: keep an "ownership decision" log per L2. acquirer / target / hybrid / new. Tie every decision to a deal-thesis citation; un-cited decisions are blocked.</item>
        <item>Treat BPMN as code. Source-control BPMN XML, run bpmnlint in CI, code-review changes, tag releases per programme milestone.</item>
        <item>Plan adoption from day one. Process docs that nobody reads have zero ROI. Bake in an adoption metric (page views, training completion, audit findings closed) and report it monthly.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Portfolio bloat. Without a Pareto rule the agent documents 800 processes at full depth. Hard-cap deep-modelling to the top decile and force narrative-only for the rest.</item>
        <item>Reference-model auto-fill. Agents lift APQC PCF text verbatim and pretend it describes the company. Require: every reference-derived sentence must be tagged [reference] and reviewed by a human before publication.</item>
        <item>M&amp;A naming collisions. Acquirer's "Order to Cash" and target's "Sales Cycle" may be the same process. Force the agent to map both names to a canonical PCF L2 code before comparison.</item>
        <item>Vendor-marketing leakage. ERP vendor reference processes embed product names ("S/4HANA Sales Order"). Strip vendor branding before publishing; otherwise diagrams look like sales decks.</item>
        <item>Cross-country smoothing. "Hire to retire" looks identical until you check tax + labour law. Force the agent to enumerate jurisdictions and flag legal-variant points.</item>
        <item>Maturity self-flattery. PEMM / CMMI self-scores trend high. Require triangulation against at least one external signal (audit finding, defect rate, conformance score).</item>
        <item>Standard-violations slipped past lint. Agents emit valid BPMN that violates internal naming convention. Run bpmnlint with custom rules, fail the artefact on violation.</item>
        <item>Hallucinated KPIs. "AP cycle time: 3.5 days" appears with no source. Hard rule: every metric cell cites file + line; otherwise "Data not available".</item>
        <item>Workaround erasure. Stakeholder transcript says "we email Brian to push the invoice through". Agent rewrites as "exception handling routes via Finance team". Require verbatim quotes for any anomaly and preserve them in evidence/anomalies.md.</item>
        <item>PII / credential / commercial-secret leak. M&amp;A diligence packs and ERP exports contain everything. Mandatory password-scrubber-agent pre-pass; additionally redact deal-pricing, salaries, customer names before any third-party SaaS upload.</item>
        <item>Cron-mode auto-advance. Stage-gate decisions are political. In headless mode, agents must freeze at stage 4 and emit a review packet - never auto-promote to stage 5.</item>
        <item>Token blow-up at portfolio synthesis. A 500-process landscape exceeds context. Chunk by L1 value chain (one L1 per worker), summarise to scorecard rows, then a final orchestrator pass over the scorecard alone.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/process-documentation.md" purpose="Current-state process doc: overview, scope, actors, steps, business rules, exceptions, metrics." />
      <template path="templates/process-analysis.md" purpose="Analysis artifact: value classification, pain points, bottlenecks, improvement opportunities, future-state summary." />
      <template path="templates/rank-portfolio.py" purpose="Script: scorecard.csv → ranked.csv (top automation/redesign candidates by NVA *feasibility)." />
    </templates>

